column16:
In the more detailed page, I tried to go back to the map but could not. It was hard to see from first glance that the 'go back' button was at the bottom

I there a direct link to that page from the start page?

When you interact with the map, you just go back to the top of the page (I thought I would be able to zoom in)

The images about the Chars has the same problem, I though I can enlarge the image, but it just took me to the top.

I could not tell the difference between the three visualizations of 'changes through time'. The first and last look the same and I don't know what changes in the second one, the caption is not clear.

In the dashboard, sometimes the texts get hidden by the visuals.

Also, some labels are partially hidden (dashboard, technical). I know the measure names are available, but I realized that late

It is better to separate population numbers by comma to read them easily ex. 1,999,999

Some values do not have currency or units, so I cannot tell if the daily income, for example, is enough

Dashboard, social: the light bulb visualization is not clear, does it represent a household? or all light bulbs in the area? how did you get the final number of bulbs
column20: dashboard, social, bowerbanks distributed: I like these types of visuals, but what does the total value represent? The visual is not read 63 from 100 so the grey bower symbols are confusing

column43: From my experience working in the humanitarian and development sector, only a few people understand the visualizations and change their interests. Data enthusiasts would found this really helpful, but general audience care more about how these figures impacts real people on the ground. So you find that most international organizations focus on sharing humanitarian stories and videos to affect the general audience emotions and interests.

column18:
The left-most column is hard to read, a table would be easier and the centered font and spacing makes it hard to focus.

I would have expected to be able to interact with the map, the whole button navigation is very unintuitive.

I cannot switch from "Asia" to "World" without going to "Bangladesh" which is weird, better have a zoom out + zoom in button instead of those changing buttons.

In a comparison I would have expected an actual interactive comparison, not just a huge list of graphs that I have to compare manually.

You pose a question "Why is it important?" without answering it. Tell me why it is important and help me make sense of the data. You show me graphs about water and energy, but what does the project do? Does it clean water? Does it give internet? Are you changing the energy sources? Or decrease consumption? All I see is a bunch of stats, why am I looking at them?!
